entifier": "1", "text": "<p>Symptoms of a broken nose may include:</p><ul><li>pain, swelling and redness</li><li>a crunching or crackling sound when you touch your nose</li><li>difficulty breathing through your nose – it might feel blocked</li><li>your nose changing shape – for example, it&#x27;s not as straight as before</li></ul><p>You may also have:</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}, {"position": 1, "identifier": "13", "@type": "ImageObject", "name": "Face of a person with a reddish-purple bruise under both their eyes and cut on their nose", "url": "https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/M3300537.max-600x600.jpg", "provider": "Science Photo Library", "license": "DR P. MARAZZI/SCIENCE PHOTO LIBRARY

https://www.sciencephoto.com/media/264194/view", "datePublished": "2017-09-25T12:46:53+00:00", "keywords": []}, {"position": 2, "identifier": "13", "@type": "ImageObject", "name": "Face of a person with several cuts on the bridge and side of their swollen nose", "url": "https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/S_0917_broken-nose_C0033040.max-600x600.jpg", "provider": "Science Photo Library", "license": "DR P. MARAZZI/SCIENCE PHOTO LIBRARY

https://www.sciencephoto.com/media/97267/view", "datePublished": "2017-09-26T11:31:41+00:00", "keywords": []}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 2, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "How to treat a broken nose yourself", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>You can usually treat a broken nose yourself. It should start getting better within 3 days and be fully healed within 3 weeks.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}, {"position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Do/Don't", "identifier": "9", "text": "<div><h3>Do</h3><ul><li><p>hold an ice pack (or bag of frozen peas) wrapped in a tea towel on your nose for up to 15 minutes, several times a day</p></li><li><p>take paracetamol to relieve pain</p></li><li><p>treat nosebleeds by sitting or standing upright and leaning forward – if possible, pinch your nose above the nostrils for up to 15 minutes</p></li><li><p>keep your head upright when lying in bed by adding more pillows – this will help to reduce swelling</p></li><li><p>read <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/cuts-and-grazes/">how to treat minor cuts and grazes</a> – if you have a small cut on your nose</p></li></ul></div>"}, {"position": 2, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Do/Don't", "identifier": "9", "text": "<div><h3>Don't</h3><ul><li><p>do not try to straighten your nose yourself if it&#x27;s changed shape – go to a minor injuries unit or see a GP instead</p></li><li><p>do not wear glasses until the swelling has gone down, unless you need them</p></li><li><p>do not pick or blow your nose until it&#x27;s healed</p></li><li><p>do not do strenuous exercise for the first 2 weeks</p></li><li><p>do not play sports for at least 6 weeks if there&#x27;s a chance your face might be hit</p></li></ul></div>"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 3, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Primary care", "identifier": "5", "text": "<h3>Go to a minor injuries unit or see a GP if:</h3><div class="block-richtext"><ul><li>your nose is crooked (not straight) after the injury</li><li>the swelling has not started to go down after 3 days</li><li>painkillers are not helping</li><li>you&#x27;re still finding it difficult to breathe through your nose after the swelling has gone</li><li>you&#x27;re having regular nosebleeds</li><li>you have a very high temperature (or you feel hot and shivery)</li></ul><p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/service-search/other-services/Minor-injuries-unit/LocationSearch/551">Find a minor injuries unit</a></p></div>"}, {"position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Emergency", "identifier": "5", "text": "<h3>Call 999 or go to A&E if you have a broken nose and:</h3><div class="block-richtext"><ul><li>a nosebleed that will not stop</li><li>a large cut or open wound on your nose or face, or something in the wound, such as glass</li><li>clear, watery fluid trickling from your nose – this could be a sign of a serious head injury</li><li>a severe headache with blurred or double vision</li><li>eye pain and double vision</li><li>neck pain or a stiff neck with numbness or tingling in your arms</li><li>a purple swelling inside your nose – it may be painful or block your breathing</li><li>other symptoms of a <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/severe-head-injury/">severe head injury</a> – such as collapsing (passing out) or difficulty speaking</li></ul></div>"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 4, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Treatment from a GP", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>A GP might prescribe stronger painkillers if paracetamol is not helping.</p><p>If you have a severe broken nose or it&#x27;s changed shape, you may be referred to a specialist in hospital for assessment and treatment.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 5, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Treating a severe broken nose in hospital", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<h3>If your nose has changed shape</h3><p>A doctor in hospital may be able to make your nose straighter using a procedure called manipulation.</p><p>You might have to go home and wait a few days for the swelling to go down first, but the procedure should be done within 14 days of you breaking your nose.</p><p>Manipulation is done using anaesthetic so that you&#x27;re asleep or your nose is numbed. It does not always make your nose look exactly the same as it was before, but it often helps.</p><h3>If you have a large wound</h3><p>The wound will usually be cleaned and sealed with stitches or strips in hospital.</p><h3>If your nose will not stop bleeding</h3><p>A doctor may place a soft gauze pad in your nose. The pad will be removed by the doctor a few days later.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}]}

Blepharitis:
{"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "MedicalWebPage", "name": "Blepharitis", "copyrightHolder": {"name": "Crown Copyright", "@type": "Organization"}, "license": "https://developer.api.nhs.uk/terms", "author": {"url": "https://www.nhs.uk", "logo": "https://www.nhs.uk/nhscwebservices/documents/logo1.jpg", "email": "nhswebsite.servicedesk@nhs.net", "@type": "Organization", "name": "NHS website"}, "about": {"@type": "MedicalCondition", "name": "Blepharitis", "alternateName": []}, "description": "Blepharitis is a condition where the edges of the eyelids become red and swollen (inflamed).", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/", "lastReviewed": ["2019-04-28T00:00:00+00:00", "2022-04-28T00:00:00+00:00"], "breadcrumb": {"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "BreadcrumbList", "itemListElement": [{"@type": "ListItem", "position": 0, "item": {"@id": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/", "name": "Health A to Z", "genre": "condition"}}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "item": {"@id": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/", "name": "Blepharitis", "genre": "condition"}}]}, "dateModified": "2020-08-10T11:17:15+00:00", "genre": "condition", "hasPart": [{"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "overview", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/#overview", "description": "Blepharitis is where the edges of your eyelids become red and swollen.", "text": "<p>Symptoms of blepharitis include sore eyelids, itchy eyes and a gritty feeling in the eyes.</p><p>You can usually treat blepharitis by cleaning your eyelids every day. If that does not work, a GP may prescribe antibiotic creams or drops.</p><p>Blepharitis can be caused by a type of bacteria living on your skin, or a skin condition like dermatitis.</p>"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "symptoms", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/#symptoms", "description": "Symptoms of blepharitis include sore eyelids, itchy eyes and a gritty feeling in the eyes.", "text": "<p>Blepharitis symptoms often come and go.</p><p>Symptoms of blepharitis include:</p><ul><li>sore eyelids</li><li>itchy eyes</li><li>a gritty feeling in the eyes</li><li>flakes or crusts around the roots of the eyelashes</li><li>red eyes or eyelids</li><li>eyelids sticking together in the morning when you wake up</li></ul>    <img  alt="S_0917_blepharitis_M1550263.jpg" height="426" src="https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/M1550263.width-640.jpg" width="640" alt="Closed eye with flakes of skin and crusts along the eyelid and eyelashes."/>", "title": "Check if you have blepharitis"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "treatments_overview", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/#treatments-summary", "description": "You can usually treat blepharitis by cleaning your eyelids every day. If that does not work, a GP may prescribe antibiotic creams or drops.", "text": "", "title": ""}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "self_care", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/#self-care", "description": "You can usually treat blepharitis by cleaning your eyelids every day. If that does not work, a GP may prescribe antibiotic creams or drops.", "text": "<br/><h3>Do</h3><ul>    <li><p>clean your eyelids at least once a day</p></li>    <li><p>continue to clean your eyes, even if your symptoms clear up</p></li></ul><br/><h3>Don't</h3><ul>    <li><p>do not wear contact lenses while you have symptoms</p></li>    <li><p>do not use eye makeup, especially eyeliner, while you have symptoms</p></li></ul><h3>How to clean your eyes</h3><ol><li>Soak a clean flannel or cotton wool in warm water and place on your eye for 10 minutes.</li><li>Gently massage your eyelids for around 30 seconds.</li><li>Clean your eyelids using cotton wool or a cotton bud. It might help to use a small amount of baby shampoo in water.</li></ol>", "title": "Things you can do to treat and prevent blepharitis"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "other_treatments", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/#treatments-other", "description": "You can usually treat blepharitis by cleaning your eyelids every day. If that does not work, a GP may prescribe antibiotic creams or drops.", "text": "<p>Your GP might suggest antibiotic creams or drops. If these do not help after 6 weeks, they may recommend antibiotic tablets.</p>", "title": "Treatment for blepharitis from a GP"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "causes", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/#causes", "description": "Blepharitis can be caused by a type of bacteria living on your skin, or a skin condition like dermatitis.", "text": "<p>Blepharitis can be caused by:</p><ul><li>a type of bacteria that lives on the skin</li><li>a skin condition, such as atopic dermatitis</li></ul><p>Blepharitis cannot be spread to other people.</p>", "title": "What causes blepharitis?"}], "relatedLink": [{"@type": "LinkRole", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blepharitis/", "linkRelationship": "Navigation", "position": 0, "name": "Blepharitis"}], "keywords": ["Blepharitis", "Antibiotics"], "mainEntityOfPage": [{"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p><b>Blepharitis causes red, swollen and itchy eyelids. It can normally be treated by washing your eyelids every day. The condition is not usually serious, but can lead to other problems, such as dry eyes, cysts and conjunctivitis, especially if it&#x27;s not treated.</b></p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Check if you have blepharitis", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>Blepharitis symptoms often come and go.</p><p>Symptoms of blepharitis include:</p><ul><li>sore eyelids</li><li>itchy eyes</li><li>a gritty feeling in the eyes</li><li>flakes or crusts around the roots of the eyelashes</li><li>red eyes or eyelids</li><li>eyelids sticking together in the morning when you wake up</li></ul>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}, {"position": 1, "identifier": "13", "@type": "ImageObject", "name": "Closed eye with flakes of skin and crusts along the eyelid and eyelashes.", "url": "https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/M1550263.max-600x600.jpg", "provider": "Science Photo Library", "license": "DR P. MARAZZI/SCIENCE PHOTO LIBRARY

https://www.sciencephoto.com/media/256626/view", "datePublished": "2017-09-22T10:43:57+00:00", "keywords": []}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 2, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<h3>If you&#x27;re not sure it&#x27;s blepharitis</h3><p>Read more about <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/eyelid-problems/">eyelid problems</a>.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 3, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": []}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 4, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Things you can do to treat and prevent blepharitis", "text": "things you can do to treat blepharitis", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Do/Don't", "identifier": "9", "text": "<div><h3>Do</h3><ul><li><p>clean your eyelids at least once a day</p></li><li><p>continue to clean your eyes, even if your symptoms clear up</p></li></ul></div>"}, {"position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Do/Don't", "identifier": "9", "text": "<div><h3>Don't</h3><ul><li><p>do not wear contact lenses while you have symptoms</p></li><li><p>do not use eye makeup, especially eyeliner, while you have symptoms</p></li></ul></div>"}, {"position": 2, "identifier": "1", "text": "<h3>How to clean your eyes</h3><ol><li>Soak a clean flannel or cotton wool in warm water and place on your eye for 10 minutes.</li><li>Gently massage your eyelids for around 30 seconds.</li><li>Clean your eyelids using cotton wool or a cotton bud. It might help to use a small amount of baby shampoo in water.</li></ol>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 5, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<h2>Ask a pharmacist how to treat blepharitis</h2><p>A pharmacist might suggest things to help keep your eyelids clean, including:</p><ul><li>eye pads and wipes</li><li>eyedrops</li></ul>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}, {"position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Find a service", "identifier": "2", "text": "<p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/using-the-nhs/nhs-services/pharmacies/">Find a pharmacy</a></p>
"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 6, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Primary care", "identifier": "5", "text": "<h3>See a GP if:</h3><div class="block-richtext"><ul><li>your symptoms do not improve after a few weeks of cleaning your eyelids</li></ul></div>"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 7, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Treatment for blepharitis from a GP", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>Your GP might suggest antibiotic creams or drops. If these do not help after 6 weeks, they may recommend antibiotic tablets.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 8, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "What causes blepharitis?", "text": "What causes blepharitis?", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>Blepharitis can be caused by:</p><ul><li>a type of bacteria that lives on the skin</li><li>a skin condition, such as atopic dermatitis</li></ul><p>Blepharitis cannot be spread to other people.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}]}

Blisters:
{"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "MedicalWebPage", "name": "Blisters", "copyrightHolder": {"name": "Crown Copyright", "@type": "Organization"}, "license": "https://developer.api.nhs.uk/terms", "author": {"url": "https://www.nhs.uk", "logo": "https://www.nhs.uk/nhscwebservices/documents/logo1.jpg", "email": "nhswebsite.servicedesk@nhs.net", "@type": "Organization", "name": "NHS website"}, "about": {"@type": "MedicalCondition", "name": "Blisters", "alternateName": []}, "description": "Read about blisters, which are fluid-filled bumps under your skin that you can get if your skin is damaged. Find out how to treat blisters yourself, how to avoid getting them, and when to get medical help.", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blisters/", "lastReviewed": ["2021-01-04T00:00:00+00:00", "2024-01-04T00:00:00+00:00"], "breadcrumb": {"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "BreadcrumbList", "itemListElement": [{"@type": "ListItem", "position": 0, "item": {"@id": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/", "name": "Health A to Z", "genre": "condition"}}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "item": {"@id": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blisters/", "name": "Blisters", "genre": "condition"}}]}, "dateModified": "2021-01-11T15:56:45+00:00", "genre": "condition", "hasPart": [{"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "overview", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blisters/#overview", "description": "Blisters are fluid-filled bumps under your skin that you can get if your skin is damaged.", "text": "<p>A blister will usually heal on its own if you cover it with a plaster or dressing and do not burst it. If it's very big or painful, a GP may drain it.</p><p>Blisters are lumps under your skin that can be filled with clear fluid, blood or pus.</p>"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "treatments_overview", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blisters/#treatments-summary", "description": "A blister will usually heal on its own if you cover it with a plaster or dressing and do not burst it. If it's very big or painful, a GP may drain it.", "text": "", "title": ""}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "self_care", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blisters/#self-care", "description": "A blister will usually heal on its own if you cover it with a plaster or dressing and do not burst it. If it's very big or painful, a GP may drain it.", "text": "<p>To protect the blister and help prevent infection:</p><br/><h3>Do</h3><ul>    <li><p>cover blisters with a soft plaster or padded dressing</p></li>    <li><p>wash your hands before touching a burst blister</p></li>    <li><p>allow the fluid in a burst blister to drain before covering it with a plaster or dressing</p></li></ul><br/><h3>Don't</h3><ul>    <li><p>do not burst a blister yourself</p></li>    <li><p>do not peel the skin off a burst blister</p></li>    <li><p>do not pick at the edges of the remaining skin</p></li>    <li><p>do not wear the shoes or use the equipment that caused your blister until it heals</p></li></ul>", "title": "How you can treat a blister yourself"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "symptoms", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blisters/#symptoms", "description": "Blisters are lumps under your skin that can be filled with clear fluid, blood or pus.", "text": "    <p><img  alt="Blister 1" height="426" src="https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/C0095259-Blister_on_heel_from_new_shoes-SPL.width-640.jpg" width="640" alt="An oval-shape bump on the skin that&#x27;s filled with clear fluid. The skin over the blister is pink and shiny."/><br/>Blisters are small pockets of clear fluid under a layer of skin</p>    <p><img  alt="Blister 2" height="426" src="https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/M7290012-Close-up_of_a_blister_after_verruca_c.width-640.jpg" width="640" alt="A round bump on the sole of the foot, just below the toes, that&#x27;s filled with dark red blood."/><br/>Blood blisters may look red or black and are filled with blood instead of clear fluid</p>    <p><img  alt="Blister 3" height="426" src="https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/C0197737-Infected_blister-SPL.width-640.jpg" width="640" alt="A round bump on the back of the heel filled with light green pus. The surface is dry and creased and the surrounding skin is red."/><br/>An infected blister can be hot and filled with green or yellow pus. The surrounding skin may look red, but this can be hard to see on darker skin tones</p><h3>Important</h3><p>Do not ignore an infected blister. Without treatment it could lead to a skin or blood infection.</p>", "title": "Check if you have a blister"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "other_treatments", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blisters/#treatments-other", "description": "A blister will usually heal on its own if you cover it with a plaster or dressing and do not burst it. If it's very big or painful, a GP may drain it.", "text": "<p>A GP might burst a large or painful blister using a sterilised needle. If your blister is infected, they may prescribe <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/antibiotics/">antibiotics</a>.</p><p>They can also offer treatment and advice if blisters are caused by a medical condition.</p>", "title": "Treatment from a GP"}], "relatedLink": [{"@type": "LinkRole", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/blisters/", "linkRelationship": "Navigation", "position": 0, "name": "Blisters"}], "keywords": [], "mainEntityOfPage": [{"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p><b>Blisters often heal on their own within a week. They can be painful while they heal, but you will not usually need to see a GP.</b></p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": []}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 2, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "How you can treat a blister yourself", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>To protect the blister and help prevent infection:</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}, {"position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Do/Don't", "identifier": "9", "text": "<div><h3>Do</h3><ul><li><p>cover blisters with a soft plaster or padded dressing</p></li><li><p>wash your hands before touching a burst blister</p></li><li><p>allow the fluid in a burst blister to drain before covering it with a plaster or dressing</p></li></ul></div>"}, {"position": 2, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Do/Don't", "identifier": "9", "text": "<div><h3>Don't</h3><ul><li><p>do not burst a blister yourself</p></li><li><p>do not peel the skin off a burst blister</p></li><li><p>do not pick at the edges of the remaining skin</p></li><li><p>do not wear the shoes or use the equipment that caused your blister until it heals</p></li></ul></div>"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 3, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "A pharmacist can help with blisters", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>To protect your blister from becoming infected, a pharmacist can recommend a plaster or dressing to cover it while it heals.</p><p>A hydrocolloid dressing (a moist dressing) can protect the blister, help reduce pain and speed up healing.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}, {"position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Find a service", "identifier": "2", "text": "<p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/service-search/find-a-pharmacy/">Find a pharmacy</a></p>
"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 4, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Check if you have a blister", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 2, "identifier": "13", "@type": "ImageObject", "name": "A round bump on the back of the heel filled with light green pus. The surface is dry and creased and the surrounding skin is red.", "url": "https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/C0197737-Infected_blister-SPL.max-600x600.jpg", "provider": "Science Photo Library", "license": "DR P. MARAZZI/SCIENCE PHOTO LIBRARY

https://www.sciencephoto.com/media/575658/view", "datePublished": "2017-06-20T14:15:43+00:00", "keywords": []}, {"position": 3, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Callout", "identifier": "4", "text": "<h3>Important</h3><p>Do not ignore an infected blister. Without treatment it could lead to a skin or blood infection.</p>"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 5, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Primary care", "identifier": "5", "text": "<h3>See a GP if:</h3><div class="block-richtext"><ul><li>a blister is very painful or keeps coming back</li><li>the skin looks infected – it&#x27;s hot and the blister is filled with green or yellow pus</li><li>the skin around the blister looks red, but this can be harder to see on darker skin tones</li><li>a blister is in an unusual place – such as your eyelids, mouth or genitals</li><li>several blisters have appeared for no reason</li><li>a blister was caused by a burn or scald, sunburn, or an allergic reaction</li></ul></div>"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 6, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Treatment from a GP", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>A GP might burst a large or painful blister using a sterilised needle. If your blister is infected, they may prescribe <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/antibiotics/">antibiotics</a>.</p><p>They can also offer treatment and advice if blisters are caused by a medical condition.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 7, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "How to prevent blisters", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>Blisters develop to protect damaged skin and help it heal. They&#x27;re mostly caused by friction, burns and skin reactions, such as an allergic reaction.</p><p>Blood blisters appear when blood vessels in the skin have also been damaged. They&#x27;re often more painful than a regular blister.</p><p>If you often get friction blisters on your feet or hands:</p><ul><li>wear comfortable, well-fitting shoes</li><li>wear new shoes for short periods of time, until they&#x27;re comfortable</li><li>wear thick socks during exercise</li><li>dust talcum powder in your socks if you get sweaty feet</li><li>wear protective gloves when you exercise or if you use tools at work</li></ul>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}, {"position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Reveal", "subjectOf": "Conditions that can cause blisters", "identifier": "11", "mainEntity": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<ul><li><a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/chickenpox/">chickenpox</a> – a childhood illness that causes itchy spots</li><li><a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/cold-sore/">cold sores</a> – small blisters that develop on the lips or around the mouth, caused by a virus</li><li><a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/genital-herpes/">genital herpes</a> – a sexually transmitted infection (STI) that most commonly affects the groin</li><li><a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/impetigo/">bullous impetigo</a> – a bacterial skin infection</li><li><a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/pompholyx/">pompholyx</a> – a type of eczema</li><li><a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/scabies/">scabies</a> – a skin condition caused by tiny mites</li><li><a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hand-foot-mouth-disease/">hand, foot and mouth disease</a> – a viral infection that usually affects young children</li></ul>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}]}]}

